  rule is the 50% rule: if the repair costs exceed 50% of the price of a new dishwasher, it’s usually better to replace
  it.</p>
<p> - <strong>Frequent Repairs</strong>: If you find yourself frequently repairing the dishwasher, those costs can add
  up quickly. Frequent breakdowns often indicate that the unit is nearing the end of its useful life.</p>
<p>3. <strong>Downtime and Operational Impact</strong>:</p>
<p> - <strong>Operational Disruptions</strong>: Consider how much downtime the dishwasher has already caused and how it
  affects your operations. Frequent failures can disrupt service and lead to lost revenue.</p>
<p> - <strong>Reliability</strong>: A new unit will likely be more reliable and come with a warranty, reducing the risk
  of future downtime.</p>
<p>4. <strong>Energy Efficiency and Operating Costs</strong>:</p>
<p> - <strong>Energy and Water Consumption</strong>: Older dishwashers tend to be less energy and water-efficient
  compared to newer models. Upgrading to an energy-efficient model can result in significant long-term savings on
  utility bills.</p>
<p> - <strong>Environmental Impact</strong>: Newer models are often designed to be more environmentally friendly, which
  can also be a selling point for eco-conscious customers.</p>
<p>5. <strong>Availability of Parts</strong>:</p>
<p> - <strong>Parts and Service</strong>: For older units, parts may become scarce or more expensive, making repairs
  more difficult and costly over time. Ensure that parts are readily available if you choose to repair.</p>
<p>6. <strong>Warranty Considerations</strong>:</p>
<p> - <strong>Existing Warranty</strong>: If your dishwasher is still under warranty, some or all repair costs might be
  covered, making repair the more economical option.</p>
<p> - <strong>New Warranty</strong>: A new unit will come with a manufacturer’s warranty, providing peace of mind and
  financial protection against future repairs.</p>
<h3>Steps to Make the Decision</h3>
<p>1. <strong>Evaluate the Current Condition</strong>:</p>
<p> - Conduct a thorough assessment of the dishwasher’s current condition. Note any recurring issues, the age of the
  unit, and its overall performance.</p>
<p>2. <strong>Get Professional Advice</strong>:</p>
<p> - Consult with an experienced commercial dishwasher technician. They can provide an accurate diagnosis of the
