<p>3. <strong>Calculate Costs</strong>:</p>
<p> - <strong>Repair Costs</strong>: Include the cost of parts, labor, and any potential downtime.</p>
<p> - <strong>Replacement Costs</strong>: Consider the price of a new unit, installation costs, and any potential
  rebates or incentives for purchasing energy-efficient models.</p>
<p>4. <strong>Consider Long-Term Benefits</strong>:</p>
<p> - Factor in long-term savings from reduced energy and water usage, improved reliability, and any potential tax
  benefits or incentives for upgrading to more efficient equipment.</p>
<p>5. <strong>Make a Decision</strong>:</p>
<p> - Based on the information gathered, weigh the pros and cons of repairing versus replacing. Consider not just the
  immediate costs but also the long-term impact on your business operations and finances.</p>
